1. 15. Rufum] P. Rutilius Sp. F. Sp. N. Rufus (11 5 47), the statesman orator and man of letters, was consul B.c. 105, and B.c. 99 legatus under Q. Mucius Scaevola when proconsul of Asia. While

acting in this capacity by repressing the illegal extortions of the tax· collectors (publicani) he incurred the hatred of the equestrian body.

Accordingly on his return to Rome he was unjustly arraigned of mal· versation (de repetundis), found guilty aud compelled to withdraw into banishment B.c. 92 (Athenaeus 1v p. 168A παρὰ δὲῬωμαίοις μνημονεύε- ται, ὥς φησι Ποσειδώνιος ἐν τῇ ἐνάτῃ καὶ τεσσαρακοστῇ τῶν ἱστοριῶν, Ἀπίκιόν τινα ἐπὶ ἀσωτία πάντας ἀνθρώπους ὑπερηκοντικέναι. οὗτος δ’ ἐστὶν Ἀπίκιος ὁ καὶ τῆς φυγῆς αἴτιος γενόμενος Ῥουτιλίῳ τῷ τὴν ῥωμαϊκὴν ἱστορίαν ἐκδεδωκότι τῇ Ἑλλήνων φωνῇ, Cicero pro Font. 5 28, Brut. 5 135, de nat. deor. 111 5 80, de orat. 1 5 229, pro Rabir. 5 27). He retired to Smyrna, where he passed the rest of his life in literary pursuits and declined Sulla’s offer to reinstate him at Rome (Valerius Maximus vl 4 5 4, ovid ep. ex Ponto 1 3, 63, et grave magnanimi robur mirare Rutili, Ι non usi reditus conclu-ione date'. Ι Smyrna virum tenuit, non Pontus et hostica tellus, Cic. pro Balbo 5 28, de nat. deor. 1115 80, de rep. 1 5 13, Tacitus ann. 1v 43, Seneca de benef. v 17, 2, cons. ad Marc. 23, 3, ep. 24, de prov. 3, 4). Athenaeus vl p. 274c tells us, doubtless on the authority of Posidonius, that he, Tubero and Scaevola were the only three Romans who observed the lex Fannia sumptuaria.
